The Journal of Drug Issues 25(4),759-782 1995
TOWARD A DRUG ABUSE TREATMENT SYSTEM
Jean Wellisch Michael L. Prendergast
M. Douglas Anglin
Drug treatment in the United States has been fragmented, underfunded, less than comprehensive, and poorly planned and integrated. To bring about a significant improvement in the number of drug abusers who receive treatment and in the effectiveness of the treatment they receive, the current fragmented approach needs to be replaced with an integrated, coherent system of drug treatment. This paperdiscusses the characteristics of a drug treatment system andfocuses on two elements of such a system: the use of the health care and criminal justice systems as locations to identify persons in needofdrug treatment, and matching clients with appropriate services to improve treatment effectiveness. The paper also discusses several issues that will needto be addressed in developing a drug treatment system, offers examples at the federal, state, and local levels indicative of trends in the direction of a systems approach to drug treatment, and emphasizes the importance offederal leadership in systems development.
Introduction
This paper offers some thoughts on the development of a comprehensive, integrated system of treatment for drug abuse in order to stimulate thinking by policy makers, researchers, and providers on a systems approach to improving drug treatment. From a health services perspective, drug treatment in the United States has never achieved its full potential for bringing about optimal outcomes with clients enrolled in treatment of all types. For a variety of historical, political, and economic reasons, drug treatment has been fragmented, underfunded, less than comprehensive, and poorly planned and integrated. Although additional funding for drug treatment is necessary to provide more effective service to larger numbers of people in need of drug treatment, much of the potential benefit of any additional funding will be lost unless we also develop a system of drug treatment that can identify drug-dependent people, deliver appropriate services, monitor progress, and provide a continuum of care matched to the needs of clients.
Jean Welllsch, Ph.D., is a Visiting Assistant Sociologist with the UCLA Drug Abuse Research Center. She has participated in two NIJ-funded projects, one as Co-Principal Investigator, on drug treatment within the criminal justice system. Her interests include criminal justice treatment for women and the development of a systems approach to drug treatment. Michael L. Prendergast, Ph.D., Assistant Research Historian, UCLA Drug Abuse Research Center, has been involved in drug abuse research for 15 years. His interests include drug treatment improvement, criminal justice treatment, drug policy, and the history of drug issues. M. Douglas Anglin, Ph.D., Research Psychologist, is director of the UCLA Drug Abuse Research Center. He has been Principal Investigator of numerous federal and state grants and contracts examining various aspects of drug treatment. Address correspondence and requests for reprints to Michael L. Prendergast, UCLA Drug Abuse Research Center, 1100 GlendonAve., Suite 763, Los Angeles, CA 90024.
