In a discussion of addiction treatment and public policy, Silverman (1985) asks why, in an age of therapeutic miracles, do we do so poorly in treating addiction? His answer is that addiction belongs to a class of lifestyle disorders with which we do poorly because such disorders require comprehensive and continuing services. He believes that the limited effectiveness of our treatment interventions can be understood in terms of weak (if not absent) linkages between general and special services, between preventive and remedial services, between segmented and holistic services, and between separated and integrated services. If the goal of treatment is to eliminate both addiction and the need for treatment (or at least the need for costly, intensive, life-intruding treatment), we must not treat addicts as a separate group but as people among other people. As Silverman puts it, if the goal is "to help the addict make the full circuit of status change from taking [drugs) to [social) conformity [without drugs or treatment]," then "addiction services must, at some points at least, be united with the mainstream of health services" (and, he might have added, social services) (Silverman 1985:197).
Frederick Glaser (1990:341), drawing on his experience in developing a systems approach to substance abuse treatment, has stated that "an underlying and fundamental factor" necessary for effective drug abuse treatment "is the taking of a systematic approach to treatment. ..Though we are accustomed to speaking of the 'treatment system,' those who have been involved in this endeavor for any length of time will immediately recognize that, in fact, such a system does not exist. To build it is the task of the future. No other contribution could facilitate effective and efficient treatment more than this."
The idea of a systems approach to drug treatment is not new. But the recent reorganization of the federal agencies involved in drug and alcohol problems, the greater emphasis in the nation's drug policy on treatment and prevention, and the opportunities and uncertainties presented by health care reform-all make this a propitious time to raise the idea of a drug treatment system again, to summarize recent thinking on the issue, and to propose steps that might be taken to move from idea to action.
Background A "war on drugs" has been a perennial theme of every administration since the
I960s, with much of the war waged against drug users. Now, hopefully, we are entering a period when the failure of a traditional enforcement strategy to control serious drug use and its concomitant problems-including increased crime, the spread of disease, and drug-exposed infants-could lead to a greater emphasis upon prevention, treatment, and rehabilitation. Several recent reports have summarized research findings supportive of the effectiveness of drug abuse treatment in reducing drug use and criminality and improving socially desirable activities (Anglin and Hser 1990; Gerstein and Harwood 1990; Kleber 1989; McLellan et al. 1992; National Association of State Alcohol and Drug~buse Directors 1990; Office of Technology Assessment 1990). Although the message that "treatment works" is becoming accepted among many federal, state, and local policy makers, there is still skepticism in some quarters regarding the strength of the research evidence and resistance toward significantly augmenting the availability of treatment. The uncertainty regarding coverage for substance abuse treatment in national health care proposals suggests that the "treatment works" message is far from being universally accepted.
Considerable evidence exists that drug treatment can be cost effective in reducing behaviors that are costly to society. For instance, compared to the costs incurred

