through drug-related crime and the costs associated with arrest, prosecution, incarceration, and community supervision, drug abuse treatment is significantly less costly. The National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors (1990) estimates the annual cost of methadone maintenance treatment at $3,000 per patient, outpatient drug-free treatment at $2,300, and residential drug-free treatment at $14,000, compared to estimated annual costs of up to $50,000 per inmate for incarceration, up to $100,000 for treating a person with AIDS, and the as yet undetermined costs of long-term care for neonatally drug-exposed infants who may require special services to treat developmental and medical problems (Goldstein and Kalant 1990). A recent study in California of the costs and benefits of treating drug abusers showed that, on average, every dollar invested in treatment saves $7.00 in crime and health care costs (Gerstein et al. 1994).
Despite the cost savings and benefits of treatment, the number of people who receive treatment is far below the number who want or need treatment. A recent report (National Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors 1990) estimates that while more than 12 million people in the United States are in need of alcohol or other drug treatment, less than 12% of these are receiving treatment, and a large number are on waiting lists to be admitted to treatment, some for as long as 6 months.
In most cases (with the exception of clients who are coerced into treatment through the criminal justice system [CIS]), a drug user is able to benefit from treatment only when he or she is motivated to obtain treatment, is able to be admitted to an accessible treatment program, and has the determination and persistence to remain in treatment until positive change occurs. Given the relatively few drug abusers who obtain treatment, the high percentage who leave treatment prematurely, and the revolving episodes of emergency room crises, detoxification, prison, and legal supervision, the present way in which we provide treatment is clearly inadequate. It is inadequate in two major ways: first, there are problems identifying people in the community and in the care or custody of the CJS who are in need of, and could benefit from, drug treatment; second, the full benefits of treatment are seldom realized, in part because treatment is available and accessible to relatively few of those in need, and in part because the available treatment options are not being optimally matched to the characteristics and needs of clients.
Identification of Drug Abusers in Need of Treatment The first limitation of current drug abuse treatment-the inadequacy in
identifying those in need of treatment-could be considerably helped through the utilization of two social systems with which many drug abusers regularly come in contact: the health care system (HCS) and the CIS. Other social service agencies such as schools might also serve as sources for identifying those in need of treatment. But a focus on developing case-finding capability in health care and criminal justice will have immediate payoff because these two systems see the largest number of drug-dependent persons, they often have procedures in place to assess individual problems (including drug problems), and at least some parts of each system have had experience in providing drug treatment and/or in referring people to drug treatment.
The Health Care System (HCS) Although publicly funded drug treatment programs tend to be separate from
mainstream health care, most drug-dependent people have multiple health and

