psychological problems, which place demands on medical and other social service agencies. Their health problems result, in part, from poverty and associated stress, poor nutrition, and inadequate hygiene; and, in part, from their drug abuse, which itself is destructive to physical and psychological health, in addition to being associated with a lifestyle where the search for drugs often takes precedence over attention to nutrition, exercise, and the practice of good hygiene. In addition, indigent drug-dependent people tend to have few employment and coping skills and few personal or family resources, both of which make it more likely that when they do seek treatment for health problems or obstetrical assistance, they will seek such care from public health care facilities, often emergency rooms. Recent studies indicate that HIV-infected persons, many of whom are injection drug users, pass through hospitals undetected, and that increasing numbers of people who visit emergency rooms, psychiatric units, and trauma centers have recently used illicit drugs (Ananth et al. 1989; Bailey 1987; Des Jarlais et al. 1988; Gordin et al. 1990; Khalsa et al. 1991; Lindenbaum et al. 1989; Peyser 1989).
Thus, because of their drug use, lifestyle, and health needs, many drugdependent people are in frequent contact with emergency rooms, physical and mental health clinics in the public sector, and (less often) HMOs and private physicians. Yet drug abuse is frequently undiagnosed when drug-dependent people are seen in these facilities, and when it is recognized, patients are often referred to treatment outside of the primary HCS. Often, however, patients may ignore referrals, and the referring organization may not be able to determine whether patients act on referrals or, if they do so, whether they receive the services they need. Thus, it is not sufficient for the HCS to develop ways to identify patients who have drug abuse problems; it is also necessary to ensure that there is a network of services and agencies to which patients can be referred and that the network include feedback mechanisms to maintain continuity of patient care and strengthen weak links within the network.
The Criminal Justice System (CJS) The other primary source for identifying those in need of drug treatment is the
CJS. At some point in their lives, most drug-dependent people come to the attention of the CJS, as well as those social agencies that use court injunction such as child protective services. Several data sources document the extent of drug use among offenders in the care or custody of criminal justice. The Drug Use Forecasting (DUF) program indicates that over half of the booked arrestees in virtually all of the 24 participating cities test positive for at least one illicit drug (National Institute of Justice 1993). In 1990, over 100,000 offenders were sentenced to state prisons for drug offenses, a tenfold increase over 1980 (Gillard 1993). In 1991, 49% of state prison inmates stated that they were under the influence of illicit drugs, alcohol, or both when they committed the offense for which they were incarcerated; also, 50% stated that they had taken illegal drugs d1:n:ing the month before committing the crime (Bureau of Justice Statistics 1993).
Because the CJS has historically been the social system that deals with the largest number of drug abusers, it also has the longest history of policy and programs to address the treatment needs of this population. Many CJS treatment efforts have been short-lived, but a few have endured. A primary example of how the CJS can be used to identify offenders in need of treatment is provided by Treatment Alternatives to Street Crime (TASC), which currently operates in over 130 sites in

