A recent U.S. General Accounting Office (1993) study concluded that TASC offers promise in helping to reduce drug abuse among offenders for two main reasons: first, the TASC model incorporates functions that have been found to be effective in reducing offenders' drug use, and, second, available research suggests that TASC clients do better than non-TASC managed offenders. The General Accounting Office (GAO) report describes the essential elements of the TASC model as consisting of coordinating treatment efforts by the CJS and treatment programs, providing incentives to offenders to enter treatment, matching offenders to appropriate treatment, and monitoring offenders with urine testing while in treatment. Drug abuse experts who were contacted by the GAO knew of no other program that incorporated all of these functions. Because of TASC's ability to identify people in the CJS who are in need of drug treatment, the National Drug Control Strategy for 1992 (White House 1992) recommended that TASC and TASClike programs be expanded.
Despite TASC's potential, the GAO report noted that, between 1987 and 1991, 13 states and one territory used only about $5 million in support of TASC, or less than 0.5% of their criminal justice block grant. Moreover, in Chicago, of the 13,000 drug offenders processed yearly in one county narcotics court, TASC screened only 1,300 to determine if they were eligible for the treatment programs. The three New York City programs visited by GAO placed only 800 offenders in treatment in 1990, while the average daily population in the city's jails is about 17,000, many of whom are drug abusers.
The example of TASC offers a two-sided message: on the one hand, TASC provides a well-developed model that has proven effective in identifying offenders who need drug treatment; on the other hand, there are relatively few TASC projects around the country, and compared to the numbers of offenders with drug abuse problems, rASC screens relatively few of them and refers fewer still into treatment. The example of TASC suggests that it will take something more than a good casefinding model to make a significant impact on the drug-dependent population within the CJS.
In summary, while the two systems-health care and criminal justice-can provide avenues for identifying drug abusers, many drug-dependent persons pass unnoticed through both of these systems. Both the CJS and the HCS need to develop better strategies and mechanisms to become more adept at performing this identification function.
Improving the Effectiveness of Treatment through Matching The limitations of drug abuse treatment today have been widely discussed (e.g.,
Gerstein and Harwood 1990; Haaga and McGlynn 1990; Schlesinger and Dorwart 1992; U.S. General Accounting Office 1990, 1991a,b). On one hand, the limitations are a direct result of inadequate resources-too few treatment programs and slots for the number of clients seeking treatment, let alone for the number in need of treatment; on the other hand, the limitations result from an insufficient range of program types employing different treatment strategies and from insufficient knowledge about how best to match available programs and services to clients with different degrees of dependence, at different periods of their addiction career, and with different social, psychological, and ethnic characteristics.

