Most researchers and treatment providers would agree that some level of matching between client and treatment program is necessary to improve treatment effectiveness and to make better use of treatment resources (Annis 1990; Brickman et al. 1982; Glaser 1980; Hser 1995; McLellan and Alterman 1991; McLellan et al. 1983). Clients bring to treatment different characteristics, including their addiction and treatment histories, goals for treatment, motivations, cognitive styles, social and economic statuses, support systems, and vocational and coping skills. By the same token, therapists and drug counselors differ in their treatment philosophies, cognitive styles, flexibility, expectations for treatment, skill, training, and experience.
Despite the potential value of matching clients to particular treatment strategies, most communities have few substantially different alternative strategies available for clients. Furthermore, no theory has yet been developed that satisfactorily provides a rationale for the development of appropriate and effective matching criteria; also, valid, reliable, and easily administered instruments to identify the most appropriate match for a particular client do not yet exist.
While we presently lack conclusive research-based information on the kinds of treatment that are most effective for different types of clients, this theoretical deficit is gradually being remedied. Some information and hypotheses on what works best are currently available from the fields of psychology, social psychology, alcohol treatment, and offender rehabilitation (e.g., Beutler et al. 1993; Friedman et al. 1993; Inciardi et al. 1993; Ries 1993; Schottenfeld et al. 1992) and studies specific to drug abuse treatment are in development.
In addition, a number of assessment instruments are currently available or are under development that provide much of the information about client needs for drug abuse and other medical, psychological, and social services (e.g., Crowe and Reeves 1994; Inciardi et al. 1992). Such instruments can help in treatment planning and in providing clients with the appropriate types and intensity of service at the program level or through other agencies with which the treatment program has strong linkages. The optimal use of such assessments, however, must occur within the context of a theoretically sound, empirically tested, and adequately funded system of organizations and services that can effectively match clients with programs and services that meet their varied needs.I
Researchers have offered a number of approaches to improving the match between clients and programs, some of which are client based, while others are program based. For example, a client-based typology proposed by Cohen (1986) starts from the premise that since addicts are not a homogeneous group, treatment should be matched to the specific needs of each type of addict. Cohen developed a classification based upon data from 663 addicts found in 10 methadone clinics and 1 therapeutic community. Client data were analyzed by cluster analysis, which resulted in nine types (clusters). Cohen presents the distinctive characteristics of each type of client and the implications for treatment for the five major types (emotionally sick, normal, professional'<criminal, inadequately socialized, and sensation-seeker). In addition to the salient characteristics of each type, Cohen indicates treatment goals, treatment techniques, staff characteristics, setting, and prognosis.
In another approach, focused more at the program level, Einstein (1986) explores the complexity of selecting a treatment strategy and lists a wide variety of factors that affect the choice of treatment strategies and methods/styles of providing treatment to clients, including the roles of counselors and therapists, tasks, therapeutic style, and expectations associated with treatment strategies. He

