Although matching strategies are promising, any such approach can only increase the likelihood of better outcome, not ensure it. Treatment is a complex process, and while some improvement can result from instituting tested matching procedures at
the client and/or program level, most improvement will come from keeping clients
under long-term management in a drug treatment system that acknowledges the chronic, relapsing nature of drug addiction and that has a variety of integrated programs and services available for clients at different stages of their treatment career, and at different life statuses (e.g., youth, women with children). Such a system would use matching procedures at each episode of treatment, monitor progress in each episode, rematch to a different type or intensity of treatment if needed, and provide continuity of care to reinforce skills learned in treatment, prevent relapse, or detect relapse early enough to reengage the client in an appropriate intervention (Brown 1989). Thus, matching becomes not just another specific treatment technique implemented haphazardly, but an integral part of a wellplanned system of treatment delivery.
The deficits discussed above in the ability to identify people in need of treatment and in providing optimally effective treatment can be largely attributed to the absence of a systematic approach in the development of the drug treatment field. Drug abuse treatment has waxed and waned over the past three decades under different administrations, under different funding priorities, and in response to changing
patterns of drug use, drug availability, and perceived national threat (Basteman 1992;
Haaga and McGlynn 1990; Musto 1987; Wellisch et al. 1993). Despite sporadic efforts by national commissions, policy advisory panels, and federal agencies to develop policies and plans to improve treatment-many of which have detailed the same or similar recommendations for what is needed-the development of drug treatment has more often than not been reactive rather than proactive, piecemeal rather than planned, and fragmented rather than integrated (McAuliffe 1990; Schlesinger and Dorwart 1992). While a systematic approach to the development of drug abuse treatment in the United States has been largely absent, such an approach is necessary if there is to be more than marginal improvements in our ability to effectively identify and treat the majority of people in need of drug treatment.
Perspectives on a Systems Approach Earlier definitions of systems tended to be based on a biological metaphor, that
is, a system was conceived of as a number of organizations, agencies, or institutions (organs) organized in such a way as to perform a societal (bodily) function. More recent definitions and conceptual models of systems have emerged out of thinking about large-scale industrial process, organizational enterprises, and social services, and about their information management needs.
