Research in the mental health sector provides an additional perspective for

understanding the development of a systems approach to drug treatment. In mental

health, according to Scott (1986:31), an increasing focus has been on the importance

of achieving greater and better coordination among varying agencies, programs, and

units and on the development of interorganizational networks. The goal has been to

develop "intentional systems" of rationalized care. Scott points out that mental

health systems tend to exhibit loose coupling among their various elements. For the

purpose of providing social services, loose coupling has advantages over tight

coupling: loosely coupled systems are better able to adapt to "heterogeneous,

conflicting, and/or changing environments," and they possess "the strengths that

accompany redundancy and overlap, beth as a repository of needed variety and

heightened responsiveness and as a safeguard against system component failure"

(Scott 1986:34).

Ideally, we would expect the development of a drug abuse treatment system to

proceed both horizontally and vertically. Horizontally, it would be linked to

community agencies and other systems that would identify those in need of treatment

and provide the special services required by the client population; it would also be

responsive to the special needs and characteristics of the communities it serves.

Vertically, the system would incorporate a wide range of alternative strategies

