More broadly, a drug treatment system would incorporate the following features: rationality, flexibility, responsiveness, delineation and awareness of purpose, shortand long-term planning, integration and articulation among parts, distribution of some functions and centralization of others, dependable funding sources, ongoing monitoring and evaluation, and capability for growth and change. In an optimal drug treatment system, the various parts would be considered together rather than separately, would be organized around a set of common goals and objectives, would follow common procedures where appropriate, would have built-in feedback mechanisms to maintain system performance, and would be aware of and responsive to larger systems (Downes and Shaening 1993).
Current Trends Toward a DrugTreatment System
On both the national and local levels, health care and criminal justice generally fit the basic description of a system, even though they are not always rational, certainly not equitable, not always aware of or in control of their parts, not always responsive to changing needs, and in other ways not fulfilling their societal function as well as they might. Drug treatment, by contrast, lacks the major elements of a "system" as defmed above. There are developments on the national and local levels, however, to indicate that it may be moving in this direction.
On the National Level Drug abuse treatment has acquired some systems aspects with formation of the
Office of National Drug Control Policy (ONDCP) in 1988 and the subsequent development of the National Drug Control Strategy, and with the more recent reorganization of the Alcohol, Drug Abuse, and Mental Health Administration (ADAMHA) into the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA). ONDCP, authorized by the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988, was created in response to the cocaine epidemic and the realization that the federal government lacked a coordinated national apparatus for its control. ONDCP has become a cabinet-level office whose purpose is to coordinate all federal efforts toward controlling illicit drug traffic and use within the guidelines of the National Drug Control Strategy. A major limitation of ONDCP has been its limited authority to enlist the cooperation of the various agencies involved in drug abuse control. Its influence was further compromised when the Clinton administration reduced its staff from 146 to 25. Nonetheless, an executive-level office with a mandate to develop national policies and strategies is an essential feature in the formation of a drug abuse treatment system.
ADAMHA, which was authorized by Congress in 1974, originally consisted of three institutes-the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH), the National Institute on Drug Abuse (NIDA), and the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism (NIAAA). In an effort to improve service delivery and research, two other agencies were later created within ADAMHA to assume the service functions of NIDA and NIAAA: the Office for Substance Abuse Prevention (OSAP) in 1986 and the Office for Treatment Improvement (OT!) in 1990.
The new agency created by the ADAMHA Reorganization Act of 1992 (PL 102321), SAMHSA, administers substance abuse and mental health prevention and treatment programs and is in the process of launching several new programs to strengthen service delivery. SAMHSA consists of three centers: the Center for

