The Center for Substance Abuse Treatment (CSAT) is mandated by the act to facilitate the development of an effective drug treatment system. Its activities include educating people at the local level on the need to establish treatment facilities, sponsoring regional workshops to improve the quality and appropriateness of treatment, funding the evaluation of treatment programs, collaborating with CSAP on outreach services, and working with the Health Resources and Services Administration and the Health Care Financing Administration to help integrate substance abuse treatment into the mainstream of U.S. health care (Alcohol, Drug Abuse, and Mental Health Administration 1992; Kleber 1993).
CSAT has recently been aggressively promoting a systematic approach to treatment and attempting to build strong linkages between drug treatment and
criminal justice. In a special issue of CSAT's TIE Communique (spring 1993), Lisa
Scheckel, then acting director of CSAT, stated "To remedy the serious unmet need for services, we all need to plan and work together-those of us in the treatment community along with policymakers and staff in all sectors of the CJS" (Center for Substance Abuse Treatment (l993a). In support of its efforts to build effective linkages between drug treatment and criminal justice, CSAT currently funds a number of related projects, including technical assistance to 35 states to help build coordinated state systems that link treatment, justice, and health agencies; training for state legislators and judicial officials on treatment issues; development of Treatment Improvement Protocols (TIPS), practical documents designed for use by state agencies; and demonstration projects that incorporate CSAT's comprehensive treatment care model and a continuum of treatment, health, and mental health services for incarcerated and nonincarcerated offenders. CSAT reports that each of their demonstration projects supports interagency criminal justice and human services linkages that include courts, corrections, probation/parole, substance abuse treatment, health and mental health, and education and work skills.
On the State and Local Level In states, counties, and cities, given funding constraints, short-term budget
cycles, and other problems, evidence of significant widespread movement toward a systematic approach is rare. Despite such hindrances, however, some changes in drug treatment are occurring on the state and local level that are in the systems direction. For example, the Treatment Alternatives for Special Clients program in I1linois screens offenders for treatment, refers clients to matched programs, and monitors clients' performance. As ~ continuation of the program's function, treatment providers for women on southside Chicago have set up a coalition that expedites the transfer of clients among several programs, and among these provides the special services required by women in different life stages (Wellisch and Falkin 1994). Several communities now separate client needs assessment and referral from the provision of treatment (e.g., the province of Ontario and the state of Minnesota have set up separate centers for assessment and referral). Under a law passed by the legislature, Colorado is establishing a comprehensive, coordinated, and continuous system of classification, assessment, and treatment for all of its drug-involved offenders (Colorado's Cooperative Plan) (Center for Substance Abuse Treatment

