While fully integrated local drug abuse treatment systems are probably few, a number of local systems are in the planning or early developmental stages. Most or all of these publicly funded systems provide treatment for clients who are referred by the CJS. However, it appears that neither the nascent drug abuse treatment system nor the CJS, separately or jointly, have a systemwide approach for identifying and treating substance-abusing offenders.
Issues in System Development In moving toward a drug treatment system, a number of important issues will
need to be resolved, two of which are discussed here: (1) Should a drug treatment system stand alone or be part of the HCS? and (2) should drug treatment and alcohol treatment be separate or combined systems?
Should a Drug Treatment System Stand Alone or Be Pan of the Health Care System (HCS)?
One of the foremost issues in developing a drug treatment system concerns the relationship between drug abuse treatment and the HCS. Historically, the treatment of drug addicts has been conducted in relative isolation from the broader systems of primary health care, mental health services, and social services. From the 1930s through the 1950s, drug treatment was largely provided by the U.S. Public Health Service narcotic hospitals in Lexington, Kentucky, and Fort Worth. Texas (Musto 1987). With the increase of drug use and its associated problems in the 1960s and the emergence of new treatment approaches such as therapeutic communities, methadone maintenance, and outpatient programs, there were attempts in the late 1960s and the 1970s to include drug treatment within mental health as part of the community mental health movement and under federal legislation that authorized funding for community mental health centers (Humphreys and Rappaport 1993). It is unlikely, however, that the attempted integration was very successful, at least not for hard-core drug addicts who were mainly treated in separate methadone maintenance programs or therapeutic communities. But whatever gains had been made to include drug treatment within community mental health services were ended with the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1981, by which the Reagan administration replaced direct federal funding of mental health and drug abuse service with block grants to the states, which largely put an end to the community mental health centers. The "war on drugs" carried out under Presidents Reagan and Bush, while it did make drug abuse a central focus of national policy, also had the effect of focusing the response to the problem on a combination of enforcement activities and stand-alone treatment programs.
Although the relative isolation of drug treatment from the HCS can be understood in a historical and political context, the question remains as to whether drug treatment should become part of health care or whether there are good reasons for keeping it (relatively) separate. Many of the writers who have been cited above come from the fields of medicine and public health, and they tend to argue that treatment for drug abuse should be incorporated into basic health care. Their belief, as indicated by Silverman (1985), is that to be truly comprehensive, services for addicts, at least for a substantial part of their treatment career. should be provided

