In terms of policy recommendations. Silverman maintains that the present strategy of expecting treatment programs to make appropriate referrals in response to the changing needs of each client works poorly. What is needed is a community health system that has general programs for people in the community and special programs for high-risk subgroups such as addicts. He would not abolish special programs for addiction treatment. such as detoxification. methadone maintenance. or therapeutic communities. but he would require such programs to compete with broad-based programs that combine special with general. remedial with preventive. segmented with holistic. and separated with integrated services. He would also require specialized programs. in order to receive funding. to demonstrate how their services fill a need within the broader context of community health care. (To a limited degree. federal agencies such as CSAT have been moving in this direction by encouraging programs applying for funding to set up arrangements with community organizations; however. at least some of these arranged services are still delivered to addicts separately. making for what Silverman [1985:199] calls a "service ghetto.tt)
