Gostin believes that the stated goal of national drug policy-to eliminate drug abuse from American society-while laudable. is impractical and even counterproductive. Current policy and practice isolates the drug abuser from the mainstream of health care; legislation and general policy. including funding priorities. have created often insurmountable barriers to treatment for many people with drug problems. In order to substantially decrease drug abuse. according to Gostin, it will be necessary to identify drug abusers and put them into a system of comprehensive and continuous care. He regards the HCS and the CJS as potential sources for effectively identifying large numbers of the most dysfunctional drugdependent people. He suggests that these two systems (health care and criminal justice). in conjunction with the currently separate drug treatment programs. could be developed into an effective system for treating drug-dependent people.

