Despite the seeming reasonableness of Gostin's view, coordination and cooperation between agencies have historically been difficult to achieve, even when agencies have similar goals and agency personnel have similar backgrounds. The reasons for this difficulty include differences across agencies in funding sources, departmental budget accountability, admission criteria, and treatment philosophy, as well as the tendency of agencies to protect their own turf and to maintain clear jurisdictional boundaries. For instance, in most communities there is little coordination between criminal justice agencies and drug treatment programs in providing alternative treatment options for offenders in various legal statuses or in ensuring continuity of care throughout offenders' drug-abusing years (Wellisch et al. 1993). Given the differences in philosophy and the orientation of personnel in drug abuse treatment, corrections, and health care, in addition to the many jurisdictional problems, Gostin's proposal to combine the three entities into a single system is likely to be difficult to achieve.
In another analysis, Dembo et al. (1983) reviewed literature of the 1960s and 1970s to identify factors that resulted in the relative isolation of drug treatment and offered a proposal to more closely integrate drug treatment programs with the communities they serve. The factors that they found to be responsible for the isolation of drug treatment included: (1) the prevailing medical model of addiction, with its implicit or explicit characterization of the drug abuser as an inadequate person; (2) the association of drug abuse with crime; (3) the development and practice of drug abuse treatment modalities by medical-psychiatric institutions and practitioners who were unfamiliar with, and insensitive to, the cultural and ethnic characteristics of the clients they were treating; (4) competition for resources with mainstream health agencies; and (5) the lack of a match between the treatment offered at particular sites and the needs and concerns of the people, particularly racial and ethnic groups, who lived in the community. (The reader is referred to the research model proposed in Dembo's article to help understand and overcome the isolation of drug treatment programs from their communities.)
Dembo and his colleagues were interested in increasing the integration of drug abuse treatment with those communities that have high rates of drug abuse and associated problems. They were looking for solutions that would lead to greater sensitivity and relevance for the affected communities. While sensitivity and relevance, particularly for minority communities, were not a major thrust of the other authors cited above, isolation from the communities being served was one of their concerns, and it could be argued that integrating drug treatment into the mainstream of public health care might lead to the development of programs and services that would be more culturally sensitive and culturally relevant for such communities.
Whether drug treatment is incorporated into mainstream health care or is developed as a relatively autonomous system, a systematic approach to drug treatment that includes all of the elements specified above is necessary. But even as a stand-alone system, drug abuse treatment would need to have very close linkages with both the HCS and the CJS for the identification of drug abusers: with the HCS providing the medical services required by most addicts; and with the CJS providing the coercion needed to get resistant clients into treatment. In addition, custody itself offers a unique opportunity (currently rarely fulfilled) for the delivery of drug treatment and rehabilitation.

