Should Drug Treatment andAlcohol Treatment Be Separate or Combined Systems?
Publicly funded treatment for alcohol and for other drugs were set up in separate programs in the early 1970s (the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism was established in 1971, the National Institute on Drug Abuse in 1973), and each has a different history, research agenda, body of research, and treatment approaches (Weisner 1992). This separation in treatment service assumed that there are alcohol abusers and drug abusers, each of whom need to be treated in different ways. But in fact most substance abusers tend to use whatever drugs, including alcohol, are available. Surveys of publicly funded treatment programs show a high percentage of multiple drug use, including alcohol (Hubbard 1990); the same is true of arrestees (National Institute of Justice 1993) and jail and prison inmates (Bureau of Justice Statistics 1991, 1993). In recent years, reflecting a recognition of this overlap in substance use patterns, as well as increased attention at all governmental levels to the need for cost containment, there has been a trend toward combining alcohol and drug treatment in terms of administration, policy, and funding, particularly at the state and local level. At the federal level, this combination is seen in the mer:fing of alcohol and drug services in the Center for Substance Abuse Treatment.
Despite this trend toward combination, there is still uncertainty as to the most effective treatments for abusers of alcohol alone, for abusers of illicit drugs, or for abusers of both. Weisner (1992) believes that at a time when each treatment field is .struggling to determine which treatment strategies and structures are most effective, it may not be appropriate to add the additional complexity of trying to treat both problems within the same system. Nonetheless, she recognizes that the current movement is in the direction of combination and that it is difficult to slow the momentum of change already begun while research is being conducted to determine the best treatment techniques. Simply knowing that many people in treatment use more than one drug is not helpful for determining the most efficacious treatment. According to Weisner (1992:70-71), "The areas of treatment outcome and health policy represent the largest research gap on combined alcohol and drug problems... Perhaps because of this lack of research, there is not much evidence that new treatment models have emerged as the systems have combined." There is some evidence, for instance, that the association between longer treatment and improved outcome, which is a consistent finding in research on drug treatment, may not hold for treatment of alcohol abuse (see Miller and Hester 1986).
An additional reason for caution in moving too quickly toward combining alcohol and drug treatment services is that alcohol abusers and drug abusers have different characteristics, which may not be easily accommodated in a combined system. Substance abusers usually have a preferred drug of choice such that it is possible to divide them into those who are primary alcohol users and those who are primary drug users. Primary alcohol users and primary drug users constitute separate populations that, despite some overlap, differ significantly in their socioeconomic and personal characteristics.3 In general, drug abusers have fewer personal resources than alcohol abusers, and are more likely to lack family support systems and social networks. They are also more likely to have criminal involvement and to have multiple contacts with the CJS. As a result, many of those who are dependent upon drugs require comprehensive habilitation and integration into the community.
Not only do the populations differ, but the legality of alcohol use and the illicit nature of drugs lead the public to express greater tolerance for alcohol than for illicit drugs and to perceive alcohol as less strongly associated with crime than drugs.

