Moreover, the isolation and ghettoization characteristic of drug treatment are not as typical of alcohol treatment. Such differences suggest that a combined alcohol-drug treatment system may be difficult to implement successfully and would likely be less effective with many patients than is currently the case with separate treatments. Unless further research and experience show otherwise, it would seem prudent not to rush into the development of a combined alcohol and drug treatment system, but rather to maintain parallel systems, with some capacity for overlap and with procedures for patients to move from one to the other as needed.
Discussion A slowly swelling chorus of voices is calling for more systemization of drug
treatment. To effect significant change, however, much more discussion, presentation of ideas, critical analysis, and delineation of issues are needed from researchers, providers, and policy makers. By way of pulling together various threads of this paper, several of the issues regarding the development of a drug treatment system are briefly discussed here.
A Federal System or Local Systems? When we talk about the drug treatment system, at what level is our perspective?
That is, should management and administration be directed from the federal level and extend through the states to the local community? Or should there be a multitude of local systems, each with its own management/administration, addressing the needs and preferences of the communities in which they are embedded, and receiving guidance, technical assistance, and financial help from the federal government?
The authors believe that, at least for the foreseeable future, a solely top-down federal system would be logistically and bureaucratically cumbersome, inefficient in operation, and poorly responsive to local needs and changing circumstances. The role of the federal government, and the states as well, should be to establish standards, set guidelines, provide technical aid, contribute fmancial support to local systems, and aggressively support research to improve the organizational structure of local systems and enhance the development of effective treatment strategies.
This position does not mean that the activities at the federal level should not be comprehensive and coordinated. A systematic approach promoted by strong leadership would encourage closer cooperation among agencies involved with substance abuse in order to better identify people in need of treatment, to place them and keep them in treatment, to develop effective treatment programs, to support research efforts, and to promote short- and long-term planning toward agreed-upon goals.
The pieces to achieve a national coordinated and cooperative effort already exist at ONDCP, SAMHSA, NIDA, and those federal agencies actively concerned with drug-abusing offenders such as the Bureau of Justice Assistance and the National Institute of Justice. What is missing is presidential leadership on this issue and an agency that recaptures the influence of the Special Action Office for Drug Abuse Prevention (SAODAP), which in the early 1970s was the instigating force in the creation of TASC and other types of linkage and had enough authority to "make heads roll. "

