Federally Sponsored Research
In order to better understand the problems of developing a full-fledged drug treatment system and to identify possible solutions, federal agencies should encourage and fund research in the following areas:
(1) Analysis of the impact on drug treatment of funding allowances and restrictions imposed by various agencies such as Medicare, Medicaid, and private health care insurance; by federal and state regulations, such as those governing methadone maintenance; and by various national health care reform proposals;
(2) Continuing research directed toward improving the ability to match client characteristics and needs with appropriate treatment services and strategies;
(3) Continuing research to develop less costly forms of treatment for those requiring comprehensive services:" these might include developing shorter intensive residential treatment programs linked with graduated continuing care services; introducing payback to the community through community service; and experimenting with treatment programs (including leadership training) based upon program models of self-sufficiency (e.g., Delancey Street);
(4) Analysis and evaluation of organizational models that would provide the best structure for emerging local treatment systems.
Federal Initiatives
Two federal initiatives should be acted upon immediately: (1) support the expansion of TASC and similar types of diversion projects throughout the country through funding and technical assistance; and (2) influence the development and growth of local treatment systems through careful selection of treatment programs for funding and through monitoring their organizational development.
Support for TASCand otherdiversion strategies
A number of studies have concluded that TASC provides one of the best examples of linkage between the CJS and drug treatment (U.S. General Accounting Office 1993; Wellisch et al. 1993). As discussed previously, the CJS provides a venue for identifying people in need of drug treatment, the means for coercing drugabusing offenders into treatment, and the opportunity for providing treatment during incarceration, probation, or parole. While the benefits to be gained by establishing additional TASC and TASC-like projects throughout the country are obvious, considerable coordination at the federal level will be needed to promote and implement this initiative,
A recent development that complements the TASC model is the emergence of drug courts as a way to provide treatment to drug-abusing defendants (Finn and Newlyn 1993; Prendergast and Maugh 1995; Tauber 1993). In a typical drug court, defendants who are charged with felony drug offenses and who are otherwise eligible for probation or diversion are offered the opportunity to enter a drug treatment program, with the charges held in abeyance until successful completion of treatment, at which time the charges are dropped. A single judge handles all cases from arraignment to graduation and sees all defendants on a regular basis to monitor their progress. This approach of centering treatment and correctional supervision of drug treatment cases in a given jurisdiction within a single court originated in Dade

