Program selection andmonitoring
Federal agencies that award grants to drug treatment programs (directly or indirectly through the states) should emphasize two main factors in their selection criteria. One factor is documentation of the apparent need within the local treatment system for the particular kind of drug treatment program that is requesting funding. That is, in making an award, the granting agency should consider not only the merits of the particular program, but also the need for this type of program within the complex of programs available in the community, and the way in which the proposed program would coordinate with other treatment programs to provide clients with a continuum of care.
The other factor concerns the arrangements made by the treatment program to obtain needed services for clients from other community agencies and organizations. Several federal agencies that fund drug treatment programs have stressed the "brokering" of services in awarding grants to programs. That is, applicants for program grants have to demonstrate that they have formal arrangements with community services of various types (e.g., hospitals, clinics, educational and vocational institutions) to provide needed services to the clients of the drug treatment program. Other agencies, such as NIl and NIDA, have funded research efforts to learn how clients' needs are assessed, how services are matched to those identified needs, and how the services are arranged for.
As indicated by Silverman (1985) and Gostin (1990), this strategy of expecting drug treatment programs to make appropriate referrals (or, better still, arrange for the provision of services from other community agencies) usually works poorly because other community agencies operate under fiscal constraints, have different eligibility criteria, and, in general, are resistant and ill-prepared to treating this population. However, until clients' needs can be serviced in the mainstream of health care, or through the decategorization of social services funding, this may be the only feasible interim arrangement. Therefore, it behooves the granting agencies to make their award criteria more rigorous to ensure that treatment programs have firm and specific service arrangements with other community agencies. Further. during the course of the grant, agencies should monitor the operation of these service agreements to see if, indeed, clients are receiving needed services in a timely and efficient manner.
Whatever else may be involved in bringing about substantial (rather than merely incremental) improvement in the number of drug abusers who enter treatment and in the effectiveness of the treatment they receive, an essential step is the development of an integrated, coherent drug treatment system. By focusing on a number of important issues involved in defining the dimensions of such a system, this paper has

